tracking. There is no hash, no coordinate, no drift status.Ok, but what about an "Implemented" table? Then an MCP tool could insert an 
(Implemented, Component) record during code generation and editing.May 18Claude responded: That's cleaner.That's cleaner. The implementation record becomes a first-class entity rather than nullable columns on Spec.
pythonclass Implemented(Model):
    build = ForeignKeyField(Build, backref="implemented", on_delete="CASCADE")
    ref = TextField()
    file = TextField()
    line = IntegerField()
    session_id = TextField(null=True)

    class Meta:
        database = db
        indexes = ((("build", "ref"), True),)
And Spec goes back to being purely about the spec itself — ref, docstring, is_template, inheritance. No nullable implementation columns.
The MCP tool libspec_implement_component writes a row here directly when it places a marker. The SpecEngine no longer needs to scan the codebase for markers at all — it just queries Implemented for the current build. The filesystem scan was always a fragile way to reconstruct state that the agent already knew when it wrote the code.
The SpecDiff then becomes:
pythonimplemented_refs = {r.ref for r in Implemented.select().where(
    Implemented.build == current_build
)}
missing = [s for s in current_specs if s.ref not in implemented_refs]
The other thing this buys you: an agent session can record implementations incrementally as it works, rather than the engine discovering them after the fact. The database reflects intent in real time, not just what the scanner found.You said: do you think it should work this way?do you think it should work this way?May 18Claude responded: Not entirely.Not entirely.
The filesystem scan is actually valuable as a ground truth check. If the database says a component is implemented but the marker isn't in the file — because the file was edited, the agent made a mistake, or the implementation was deleted — the database is lying. Trusting the agent's self-reported Implemented records exclusively means the spec graph can drift from reality silently, which is ironic given how much effort went into preventing exactly that.
The two sources serve different purposes:

The Implemented table records intent — the agent said it implemented this ref, in this file, at this line, during this session.
The filesystem scan records reality — the marker is actually there right now.

Rather than choosing one, reconciling them is more honest. The SpecEngine could compare the two and surface discrepancies as a lightweight sanity check — not the full drift detection machinery, just "this ref is recorded as implemented but the marker isn't where we expect it." That's a single grep or readline per claimed implementation, not a full workspace scan.
The SpecDiff then has three states instead of two: missing (no record, no marker), implemented (record and marker agree), and unverified (record exists but marker not found at the recorded location). Agents and humans can decide what to do with unverified — it's a signal, not an error.
This keeps the Implemented table as the primary source for performance, while the filesystem remains the authority for correctness.You said: so, the implemented table could produce a hash of the component and include that in the code gen, # implemnted <id> <hash>; what do you think?so, the implemented table could produce a hash of the component and include that in the code gen, # implemnted <id> <hash>; what do you think?May 18Claude responded: That's drift detection coming back in through the side door — and honestly, in this form it's much more tractable than the original approach.That's drift detection coming back in through the side door — and honestly, in this form it's much more tractable than the original approach.
The original coordinate dilemma was hard because the hash had to be computed from the code after the fact, which meant parsing, canonical serialization, nested marker problems, and all the rest. Here it's the opposite: the hash is computed from the spec before the code is written, and embedded in the marker at generation time. The spec is stable, well-structured English prose in the database — hashing it is trivial.
# IMPLEMENTS: spec.services.MyService a3f8c2d1
Verification is then cheap and unambiguous: read the marker, extract the hash, look up the spec in the database, hash the current docstring, compare. No AST parsing, no canonical serialization, no Tree-sitter. Just a string hash.
What it catches is also well-defined: the spec changed after the implementation was written. Not "did the code change" but "does this implementation still claim to satisfy the spec it was written against." That's actually the more useful question — spec changes are the thing the agent needs to know about, not code reformats.
The Implemented table gains a spec_hash column, the marker embeds it, and the reconciliation check becomes: recompute the hash from the current spec row, compare to the marker. Discrepancy means the spec evolved and the implementation needs review.
That feels like the right scope for drift detection — lightweight, spec-side, no code parsing required.You said: please update the specstoreresolution.please update the spec_store_resolution.mdMay 18Claude responded: The key changes:Edited 6 files, viewed a file, read a fileEdited 6 files, viewed a file, read a fileThe key changes:
