Section 1 was softened — drift detection doesn't go away entirely, it just gets scoped correctly. The conclusion says the same.Spec store resolutionDocument · MD DownloadYou said: one thing about storing components in the back end.one thing about storing components in the back end. They need be installed all at once as part of a "build", but maybe there is a better name for it.  what I mean is that I don't want each component passed across the store layer interface boundary one by one, i want to insert an entire build all at once. that are a set of components that all belong to the same source spec.  Am I making sense?8:12 AMClaude responded: Yes, completely.Yes, completely. A build is an atomic unit — all the components compiled from a given spec/*.py source tree, inserted together in a single transaction. Either the whole thing lands or none of it does. Partial builds are worse than no build.
The interface probably looks more like:
pythonclass SpecStore(Protocol):
    def store_build(self, components: list[Component], edges: list[Edge]) -> Build: ...
    def get_component(self, ref: str, build: Build) -> Component | None: ...
    def list_components(self, build: Build) -> list[Component]: ...
    def current_build(self) -> Build | None: ...
store_build takes everything at once and wraps it in a single transaction internally. The caller — the SpecEngine — compiles the full graph first, then hands it over in one call. The store layer never sees a partial state.
As for naming — "build" is fine mechanically but it carries connotations of compilation pipelines and CI. What you're really describing is a snapshot of the spec graph at a point in time: all the components derived from a coherent set of source specs, together. Snapshot might be more expressive. Or Revision if you want to emphasize its place in a sequence.
Snapshot feels right to me — it says "this is the complete state at this moment" without implying anything about how it was produced.You said: what are the edges?what are the edges?8:13 AMClaude responded: Good catch — they're redundant at the interface boundary.Good catch — they're redundant at the interface boundary.
The edges are the inheritance relationships between components, but the Component already knows its parents via the inherits: list[str] field. The SpecEngine compiler resolved the MRO and put it there. So by the time store_build is called, the edge information is already inside the components themselves.
The store layer can derive the Edge rows from component.inherits internally during store_build — it doesn't need them passed in separately. The interface simplifies back to:
pythonclass SpecStore(Protocol):
    def store_snapshot(self, components: list[Component]) -> Snapshot: ...
    def get_component(self, ref: str, snapshot: Snapshot) -> Component | None: ...
    def list_components(self, snapshot: Snapshot) -> list[Component]: ...
    def current_snapshot(self) -> Snapshot | None: ...
Clean boundary. The caller thinks in Component objects. The store thinks in rows and edges. Neither leaks into the other.You said: so, a snapshot of the spec is the abstract spec.so, a snapshot of the spec is the abstract spec.8:14 AMClaude responded: Right.Right. And that reframes the whole thing clearly.
The spec/*.py source files are the abstract spec. The snapshot is the compiled, persisted form of that abstract spec at a point in time — queryable, diffable, shippable. The Implemented table is separate and sits alongside it, recording what the concrete codebase has claimed to satisfy.
So the two concerns that were tangled together from the beginning finally have clean names:

Abstract spec → Snapshot (compiled from spec/*.py, stored in Spec and Edge rows)
Concrete state → Implemented (recorded by agents via MCP tool, stored in Implemented rows)

And the SpecDiff is the delta between them — which refs exist in the current snapshot but have no corresponding Implemented record, or whose Implemented record has a stale spec hash.
The SpecEngine mediates between the two. It never conflates them. That's the clean architecture the original document was reaching for but couldn't quite land because the two concerns kept bleeding into each other.You said: no the concrete spec is the list of components.no the concrete spec is the list of components.8:15 AMClaude responded: You're right, sorry.You're right, sorry.

Abstract spec → the spec/*.py source files
Concrete spec → the Snapshot — the compiled list of Component objects, persisted in the database
Implementation → the Implemented records — what the codebase claims to have satisfied

The SpecEngine compiles the abstract spec into the concrete spec. The concrete spec is what agents and tools actually work against — they never read spec/*.py directly. The Implemented table records what the codebase has done relative to the concrete spec.
Three distinct layers, each with a clear name.You said: each component has a hash associated with it, this is a current hash of the rendered docstring text of the component, the current hash of all the inherited com…each component has a hash associated with it, this is a current hash of the rendered docstring text of the component, the current hash of all the inherited components.8:18 AMClaude responded: So the hash is a content fingerprint of the full rendered spec for that component — not just its own docstring but the complete inherited text as the agent wou…So the hash is a content fingerprint of the full rendered spec for that component — not just its own docstring but the complete inherited text as the agent would see it. Which means if any ancestor's docstring changes, the component's hash changes too, even if the component itself wasn't touched.
That's the right design. The hash answers "what was the complete spec this implementation was written against" — including everything it inherited. A change anywhere in the ancestry invalidates the hash, which is correct because the implementation was written against the combined meaning, not just the leaf docstring.
So at snapshot time the engine:

Renders each component's full docstring, including inherited text resolved in MRO order
Hashes the rendered output
Stores the hash alongside the component in the Spec row

And the Implemented record stores that hash at the moment the agent claimed to satisfy the component. Verification is then: recompute the hash from the current snapshot, compare to the stored hash in Implemented. If they differ, the concrete spec changed after the implementation was written — unverified.
