The multiuser dimension also puts pressure on the append-only log. With multiple users potentially snapshotting concurrently, "current snapshot" needs a clearer definition — is it the latest globally, or the latest per user, or the latest that was explicitly marked as canonical? That's worth deciding before the schema is locked.You said: here's the thing, we might have many people developing a spec concurrentlyhere's the thing, we might have many people developing a spec concurrently8:24 AMClaude responded: That changes the shape significantly.That changes the shape significantly. A snapshot can no longer be "the compiled output of the full spec tree" because there is no single full spec tree — different people are working on different parts of it simultaneously.
So a snapshot probably needs to become more granular. Instead of one snapshot per full build, you have snapshots per module or per subtree of the spec, and the current concrete spec for a project is the composition of the latest snapshot per module across all contributors.
Which raises the question of how the abstract spec is partitioned. Is each spec/*.py file an independently ownable unit? Is it by namespace — spec.services.* belongs to one team, spec.core.* to another? Or is ownership more fluid than that?
The answer shapes whether the granularity is at the file level, the subtree level, or something else entirely. And it affects how the SpecEngine computes component hashes — if a component's ancestor is owned by someone else and their snapshot is newer, the hash of your component changes even though you didn't touch it.
